		<div>That person seems to have an agenda...anyway, from my own experiences of the odd n' very weird, while it's always possible I may be delusional (or <i>you</i>...are you real or just part of The Matrix? *evil grin*), the problem is, other folks experienced some of these strange events, at the same time, and some were not part of a group or knew what was occuring. Thus, you either have telepathy, or an actual unusual event.<br />
-Just because something is weird and outside the norms, does not mean therefore that whoever experiences it is automatically a nutcase, FFS! that's not Science, that's religious hysteria, like the bloody Inquisition: <i>&quot;If you're not supportive of us, you're obviously mad!&quot;</i> <br />
-Eat my shorts! :D<br />
<br />
The typical explanation for these things, currently, when their &quot;(the extreme skeptics) schizophernia&quot; posture breaks down, is that <i>&quot;it's all caused by magnetism!&quot;</i>...which is obviously bullsh*t because the magnetic fields required to induce hallucinations are, iirc, 10,000+ times stronger than that found anywhere on the Earth's surface, and would be sure as hell noticeable if they did occur. Since those have NEVER been seen, nothing like that at all, it's bullshit. <br />
-You can have hallucinations by brain injury, poison/drug, extreme magnetic field, and other trauma, that's perfectly fine and logical, however, when you can just label someone &quot;schizophrenic&quot; without an actual physical test to prove this is actually the case...that's <i>very </i>dangerous. Think about it a while.<br />
<br />
-Real problem is, that the folk behind this are nutbars themselves. Go check up on the amount/type criminality, insanity professional misconduct of the psychiatric profession, it's rather telling (and sad for the actual decent members of the profession)<br />
<br />
And yes, I do have a chip on my shoulder, two, actually: one being that, thanks to the hubristic asshattery of psychiatrists demanding that thier theory of &quot;M.E. = Psychosomatic Illness&quot; was the only possible explanation, the first two GPs who I saw to try and get help for my M.E., regarded it as &quot;hysterical, it doesn't exist!&quot;, when in fact it most certainly does, it's a neurological illness that some psychiatrist bastards decided to have as &quot;their pet illness&quot; and ignored all the damned evidence that it's physical in origin, leaving millions across the world to suffer and die...so, I hate them, bitterly so. Same vermin in decades past, called folk who had Type II diabetes or Multiple Sclerosis, &quot;Hysterically lazy&quot;. <br />
-If you require hard proof, in my case, MRI shows lesions on the brain and shadow on the pituitary gland, blood tests show gross failure in pituitary output that triggers testosterone, hence I have to get hormone therapy. So...those GPs, also an endocrinologist who couldn't be arsed to do his work because he had the same attitude (ME = mental case and lazy) and that section of th epsychiatric lobby at the root of this, were full of sh*t. I can supply you with a *lot* more evidence in that vein if you wish. In my opinion as a victim, those psychiatrist swine are criminals.<br />
<br />
Second point being, I've HAD &quot;supernatural&quot; experiences, and know more about it than some conceited w*nker who doesn't.  <br />
Those events occured many years <i>before </i>getting M.E. I can explain those events in detail if you wish. Oh, and having an MRI (which is a gigantic electromagnet) did NOT induce delusions in me, fyi....noisy as hell, but that's all :D<br />
<br />
I DO have psychologial issues, from gross abuse as child, and then later form the brain damage of this illness and the psychological effects of a painful, debilitating illness. In the case of the former, I learned to deal with and over come them to a large extent, you can't simply &quot;cure&quot; them though,  they are &quot;scars&quot; I'm sure many of the folk here have had similar woes,...but a lot of my family have what's reffered ot as &quot;the Second Sight&quot;, and I never did drugs or suffered fom depression, needed psychiatric help etc. I may have had a few screws loose, but I was not crackers, <i>biiiiiig </i>difference ;) I sought the help of a psychologist when the M.E. got os bad I was suicidal (it's a very, very bad illness, believe me), the psychologist was a very nice perosn, very helpful, but she could offer little professional help as I'd figured out for myself most of the coping stratgies, her kindness and Humanity though were very helpful. I'm not against good psychology or neurology, I just have a &quot;bee in me bonnet&quot; about arrogant swine who have forgotten their role' as physicians.<br />
<br />
<br />
Thus, while it is possible Jesus etc may have been delusional, the condescending, smary arrogant attitude from the article in OP, is probably a product of someone who's out ot bash religion, rather than prove a possible logical point.<br />
-Folk always need to remember much of what's written in the Bible, is crap, it never happened, or was badly interpreted and re-written over generations etc. People back then simply didn't understand as much as we do and thus couldn't comprehend or explain many things etc. While I do believe in the supernatural, this doens't mean that the events said ot have occured did, <i>or did not</i>. Very useful as spiritual, philosophical text, and a historical document, but it it s not a book of &quot;hard facts&quot;.<br />
-The Illiad is a fanastic story, partially fact, partially fiction, and alas, re-copied ove rthe centuries so how close it is ot the original text....? Thus, those who believe the Bible as LITERAL fact are as foolish as someone who says <i>The Illiad is all literal fact</i>.<br />
<br />
So, to say that &quot;<i>Jesus was delusional because he said he walked on water</i>!&quot; is in itself, either insane or spoken by someone who never bothered to actually study the hsitory of Jesus and the Bible at all: ie, a gum flapping twat :D</div>
